1
00:00:04,677 --> 00:00:05,314
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:05,314 --> 00:00:06,240
Brothers in Oath

3
00:00:06,240 --> 00:00:15,120
It has been a long day and Timucin is very tired, 
but that is unimportant. He looks at the arrow  

4
00:00:15,120 --> 00:00:22,880
he has just been given and tries to remember if 
he has ever seen anything as beautiful before.

5
00:00:24,480 --> 00:00:30,400
The arrow is far more decorated than all 
the others he has seen. And he has seen  

6
00:00:30,960 --> 00:00:40,640
a lot of arrows. After all, his father is the khan 
- and not just any khan, but the most powerful and  

7
00:00:40,640 --> 00:00:49,200
feared for many days' ride. His yurt is full 
of the most splendid bows and arrows hanging  

8
00:00:49,200 --> 00:00:58,960
on the walls. Often, other tribes come to visit. 
These tribes have beautiful weaponry too. Not just  

9
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:07,280
spears, shields and glinting swords, but artfully 
carved bows and even more exquisite arrows.

10
00:01:08,960 --> 00:01:16,320
So far, he has never seen an arrow like 
this one. It is longer than his arm,  

11
00:01:16,320 --> 00:01:22,880
not as long as the arrows the men use, but at 
least two hands longer than the ones he and the  

12
00:01:22,880 --> 00:01:31,120
other boys use to practise - and the carvings are 
so detailed that he is almost afraid to touch it.  

13
00:01:32,720 --> 00:01:36,640
The arrowhead is not made of iron, but of bronze.  

14
00:01:37,440 --> 00:01:44,320
This makes it weak and practically useless against 
anything with even thick fur, let alone against  

15
00:01:44,320 --> 00:01:51,360
hardened leather or plate armour. Then again, 
this kind of arrow is not intended to be used  

16
00:01:51,360 --> 00:01:59,440
like that. The soft metal has been engraved 
with artful lines and symbols, and the edges  

17
00:01:59,440 --> 00:02:07,840
have been so carefully polished and sharpened 
that it could probably split a hair in half.

18
00:02:08,880 --> 00:02:12,800
As he looks at it, Timucin is ashamed.

19
00:02:14,480 --> 00:02:17,760
"It is... it is beautiful,"  

20
00:02:18,400 --> 00:02:25,680
he says. "I've never seen anything 
so beautiful. You are a true artist."

21
00:02:27,360 --> 00:02:36,080
Chuzir pulls a face as if Timucin has just said 
something indecent or spoken badly of the gods.  

22
00:02:36,080 --> 00:02:43,360
He too holds an arrow in his hand, the one that 
Timucin has given him in return for this stunning  

23
00:02:43,360 --> 00:02:52,560
work. He is almost convincing as he pretends to 
admire it, even if there is very little to admire.  

24
00:02:53,200 --> 00:03:00,720
It is a completely normal arrow, short and not 
even entirely straight. Timucin has polished  

25
00:03:00,720 --> 00:03:08,080
the iron head as much as he can and added 
a few simple carvings with as much skill  

26
00:03:08,080 --> 00:03:15,280
as his clumsy fingers allow. Chuzir is 
kind enough not to say anything about it.

27
00:03:17,120 --> 00:03:24,960
"I am no artist," answers Chuzir after a 
noticeable pause and in an almost offended tone  

28
00:03:24,960 --> 00:03:32,720
of voice. "Soon, I shall be a warrior," he adds 
with a sideways glance in Timucin's direction,  

29
00:03:32,720 --> 00:03:39,600
"although I shall never be a khan, of course." 
He says these last words reproachfully.

30
00:03:41,040 --> 00:03:43,840
"But this arrow..." says Timucin.

31
00:03:44,720 --> 00:03:52,960
"I did not make it," interrupts Chuzir. "It was 
old man Schezen who did the carving. In return,  

32
00:03:52,960 --> 00:04:00,880
I helped him collect firewood and peat for three 
moons." He looks at Timucin. "Do you not like it?"

33
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:09,760
"Of course," says Timucin quickly, "it's 
wonderful. But my own arrow is so..." He stops,  

34
00:04:09,760 --> 00:04:16,080
embarrassed, but Chuzir just 
laughs and jabs him in the ribs  

35
00:04:16,080 --> 00:04:23,200
so hard that Timucin will start crying if he does 
not stop himself with all the strength he has.

36
00:04:24,560 --> 00:04:27,840
"That's not the point," says Chuzir, laughing,  

37
00:04:28,560 --> 00:04:34,480
"because you probably needed just as much 
time to carve it as I spent helping that  

38
00:04:34,480 --> 00:04:41,600
rip-off merchant Schezen carry wood whilst 
he sat by the fire keeping himself warm."

39
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:46,960
Perhaps that is true, thinks 
Timucin. Nevertheless, he is ashamed  

40
00:04:46,960 --> 00:04:55,360
of the gift. If this were someone else, he 
would suspect them of trying to embarrass him  

41
00:04:55,360 --> 00:05:05,120
by making such an exaggerated gift; but not 
Chuzir. Chuzir is his best friend, his only friend  

42
00:05:05,120 --> 00:05:13,680
even - despite the fact that he is the khan's son. 
Or perhaps it is because he is the khan's son...

43
00:05:15,520 --> 00:05:20,800
"Come on," says Chuzir, jabbing him in the 
ribs again, "let's go and try them out!"

44
00:05:22,480 --> 00:05:30,400
Just the very idea of shooting this exquisite 
arrow and perhaps damaging it fills Timucin  

45
00:05:30,400 --> 00:05:38,320
with horror, but Chuzir has already turned on 
his heels and run off, so Timucin follows him.

46
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:46,480
He runs as fast as he can, but he just cannot 
keep up with Chuzir and will probably lose him.  

47
00:05:47,760 --> 00:05:54,400
Chuzir sees that his best friend is having 
trouble and slows down, then stops entirely.  

48
00:05:55,520 --> 00:06:01,680
Nevertheless, Timucin is completely out of 
breath when he too gets to the top of the hill.  

49
00:06:02,560 --> 00:06:07,040
Chuzir does not say anything, but he 
cannot stop himself from grinning.  

50
00:06:07,040 --> 00:06:09,680
Not that he tries for one moment, either.

51
00:06:10,640 --> 00:06:18,240
"I bet I get to the trees before you!" Chuzir 
says. He is not even breathing heavily, while  

52
00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:26,080
Timucin's lungs are burning like fire and his 
heart is beating so hard he thinks it might burst.

53
00:06:27,040 --> 00:06:33,160
"What a cheek!" thinks Timucin to 
himself, and then he turns to Chuzir.

54
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:39,680
"Why don't you just tell me what I have to 
do for you?" he asks grumpily. "After all,  

55
00:06:39,680 --> 00:06:45,360
I shall have to do it anyway when I lose the 
bet. So I might just as well save my strength."

56
00:06:46,720 --> 00:06:51,440
Chuzir grins and makes as if 
to jab him in the ribs again,  

57
00:06:51,440 --> 00:06:59,440
but he just runs around and starts strolling 
towards the woods. Timucin follows, cursing  

58
00:06:59,440 --> 00:07:06,640
himself for what he has just said. Of course, 
Chuzir will never tell anyone anything about it.  

59
00:07:06,640 --> 00:07:13,600
Timucin is his friend, after all, and they are 
about to become brothers in oath. Yet if one of  

60
00:07:13,600 --> 00:07:20,480
the other boys has heard what he has said, then 
it will just lead to more rumours in the village.  

61
00:07:21,120 --> 00:07:29,840
And his father will not like that at all! He 
will have to be more careful about what he says.

62
00:07:31,200 --> 00:07:34,560
The two young warriors reach 
the trees at the same time.  

63
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:42,560
Chuzir takes his bow from his shoulder, loads it 
with Timucin's arrow and, inspecting it closely,  

64
00:07:42,560 --> 00:07:50,240
draws it halfway back. There he holds it, 
waiting until Timucin too has cocked his bow.  

65
00:07:51,200 --> 00:07:58,880
He nods the signal to shoot and then draws back 
his bow in a movement as smooth as it is strong.

66
00:08:00,240 --> 00:08:01,840
"Forever," he says.

67
00:08:03,120 --> 00:08:05,520
"Forever," echoes Timucin.

68
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:15,680
Their arrows fly off with a twin crack. 
Despite being too short, bent and warped,  

69
00:08:16,480 --> 00:08:24,000
Timucin's arrow, sped by Chuzir's bowstring, flies 
almost twice as far as the richly decorated work  

70
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:32,080
of art that he himself has shot off. It must have 
flown at least two hundred paces, perhaps even  

71
00:08:32,080 --> 00:08:38,000
three hundred, before burrowing into the ground 
halfway between the trees and the riverbank.

72
00:08:39,520 --> 00:08:45,840
"Forever", says Chuzir once again; and 
this time, too, Timucin echoes him.

73
00:08:47,720 --> 00:08:56,320
Chuzir is beaming. A warm feeling comes 
over Timucin, accompanied nevertheless  

74
00:08:56,320 --> 00:09:02,240
by a strange feeling of emptiness, 
almost of disappointment.  

75
00:09:04,160 --> 00:09:11,680
So now they are brothers in oath. They have 
been talking about it since last summer  

76
00:09:11,680 --> 00:09:18,080
and have made preparations accordingly, 
and somehow, he expected it to be... well,  

77
00:09:18,880 --> 00:09:25,280
more dramatic. Taking an oath together 
is more than being brothers by birth;  

78
00:09:26,160 --> 00:09:33,280
it means being bound together forever, being two 
parts of a whole who just happen to live in two  

79
00:09:33,280 --> 00:09:40,160
different bodies. From this day forth, he will be 
willing to give his life to protect his brother  

80
00:09:40,160 --> 00:09:49,040
if need be, and he expects this thought to be 
somehow... elevating. Shouldn't the earthquake  

81
00:09:49,680 --> 00:09:55,680
and the heavens open? Shouldn't there at least 
be a thunderclap and a few flashes of lightning?

82
00:09:56,800 --> 00:09:59,280
Yet there is nothing, of course.  

83
00:10:00,560 --> 00:10:08,240
Chuzir embraces him briefly and then turns 
away brusquely. "Let's go and get the arrows."

84
00:10:10,880 --> 00:10:18,080
They do not run this time, but Chuzir has 
almost twice as much ground to cover as Timucin  

85
00:10:18,080 --> 00:10:23,840
to reach his arrow and, for some reason, 
Timucin does not want to follow him.

86
00:10:24,880 --> 00:10:29,920
He pulls the precious arrow from the 
ground and wipes it down carefully.  

87
00:10:31,200 --> 00:10:34,160
Suddenly he has an intense feeling  

88
00:10:34,880 --> 00:10:41,680
of being watched. Perhaps the other young 
warriors had found out what they were doing?

89
00:10:43,600 --> 00:10:46,880
Timucin turns round and stiffens.  

90
00:10:47,760 --> 00:10:55,280
His hunch is true. Except that he is not 
just being watched, he is being stalked.

91
00:10:56,720 --> 00:11:02,800
It's a dog, almost as big 
as a foal, but far heavier.  

92
00:11:03,760 --> 00:11:10,080
It is a shaggy-coated monstrosity with 
huge teeth, dripping with yellow slaver.  

93
00:11:10,960 --> 00:11:19,200
And it is standing about ten paces behind him 
at the edge of the forest, staring at him.

94
00:11:20,880 --> 00:11:28,400
Timucin can feel his heart faltering. He hates 
dogs and is afraid of them more than anything  

95
00:11:28,400 --> 00:11:35,520
else in the world. He grips the arrow tighter, 
but, although his life might now depend on it,  

96
00:11:35,520 --> 00:11:43,120
something seems to be stopping him from 
drawing the bowstring. The dog might kill  

97
00:11:43,120 --> 00:11:50,240
him. Perhaps it does not want to, but it can 
- and this thought is more than he can bear.

98
00:11:51,520 --> 00:11:58,720
"Timucin, shoot!" cries Chuzir at almost the 
same moment as he releases his bowstring.  

99
00:11:59,440 --> 00:12:02,640
The arrow whizzes past Timucin's cheek,  

100
00:12:02,640 --> 00:12:08,800
stroking him with its feathers. As the arrow 
hits the ground just over a man's length away  

101
00:12:08,800 --> 00:12:15,680
from the dog, it lets out a frightened yelp 
and runs off with its tail between its legs.

102
00:12:16,960 --> 00:12:26,800
"Timucin, shoot!" shouts Chuzir again, "What are 
you waiting for?" Timucin hears Chuzir's steps  

103
00:12:26,800 --> 00:12:34,000
and sees the huge dog bolting like a hare towards 
the trees and disappearing into the undergrowth.  

104
00:12:35,440 --> 00:12:42,080
Chuzir reaches him, tears the arrow from 
his fingers and, faster than Timucin's eyes  

105
00:12:42,080 --> 00:12:48,160
can follow, loads it into his bow. He draws 
the string back behind his ear and then...  

106
00:12:48,880 --> 00:12:54,880
He lets out a moan as he drops 
the bow. The dog is gone.

107
00:12:56,640 --> 00:13:02,160
"Why did you do that?" he asks 
angrily. "Why didn't you shoot?"

108
00:13:03,520 --> 00:13:13,840
"Because, er, because the arrow..." stutters 
Timucin. Chuzir looks at him with a frown  

109
00:13:13,840 --> 00:13:18,080
and Timucin continues to 
speak, with a nervous smile.

110
00:13:19,520 --> 00:13:23,360
"I was afraid of breaking 
it, as it is so valuable..."

111
00:13:24,880 --> 00:13:30,240
This only makes Chuzir angrier, 
but he says nothing more,  

112
00:13:30,240 --> 00:13:36,240
pressing his lips together out of rage and 
stomping off past him to fetch his dart.

113
00:13:38,160 --> 00:13:41,440
Timucin knows what will happen in the night.  

114
00:13:42,480 --> 00:13:47,840
The dragon will come to him and 
show him what he has missed.
 
 
 

115
00:13:47,840 --> 00:13:51,440
CHAPTER TWO

116
00:13:51,440 --> 00:13:52,800
The Dream Dragon

117
00:13:55,040 --> 00:13:58,720
Timucin goes to bed unusually early this evening.  

118
00:13:59,600 --> 00:14:06,960
Most evenings, his mother has to tell him to go 
and leave the men to sit round the fire in peace,  

119
00:14:06,960 --> 00:14:15,680
as is their right. All too often, he stays up 
until his father puts his foot down. Only then  

120
00:14:15,680 --> 00:14:23,200
does he do as he is told and goes into his little 
yurt, pitched right next to his father's tent.  

121
00:14:24,800 --> 00:14:31,360
He has been sleeping alone here since 
last summer. Today, however, he cannot  

122
00:14:31,360 --> 00:14:38,320
wait to go. He gulps down his dinner, makes 
an excuse and goes to bed before sunset.

123
00:14:39,520 --> 00:14:47,440
As is always the case when trying to sleep, it 
takes a long time for him to sink into slumber.  

124
00:14:48,560 --> 00:14:56,320
He has barely fallen asleep when Sarantuya 
comes to him. Just like every time,  

125
00:14:56,320 --> 00:15:04,480
Timucin feels her presence more than he sees 
it. Well, in the first moments in any case.  

126
00:15:05,520 --> 00:15:12,160
It is something big, infinitely 
soft but also infinitely old  

127
00:15:12,160 --> 00:15:19,360
and strong that steals into his dreams 
and only slowly takes on a form.

128
00:15:20,480 --> 00:15:23,280
"I haven't seen you for a while," he says.

129
00:15:24,480 --> 00:15:32,240
"I didn't feel that you needed me," answers 
Sarantuya. The shadowy figure in his dream  

130
00:15:32,800 --> 00:15:40,320
starts to become clearer. At the edge 
of his consciousness, something big,  

131
00:15:41,040 --> 00:15:51,360
something ancient stirs, glinting like 
moonlight on silver scales. It touches his soul.  

132
00:15:52,720 --> 00:16:01,920
He feels warmth and comfort and thinks 
he almost sees something. Almost.

133
00:16:04,080 --> 00:16:08,080
"Why did you do that?" asks Timucin.

134
00:16:08,080 --> 00:16:16,720
Sarantuya squints, as the moonlight in the 
dream breaks on her scales and then flows down  

135
00:16:16,720 --> 00:16:25,040
her flanks, jingling lightly as if, somewhere 
far away, a thousand cymbals are being struck.  

136
00:16:26,720 --> 00:16:34,000
It is always night in Timucin's dreams when 
Sarantuya comes to him, and there is always  

137
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:42,320
a full moon. He has stopped being surprised 
by it. "What did you say?" she asks him.

138
00:16:43,520 --> 00:16:50,000
Timucin has to force himself not to 
get angry; despite her huge claws  

139
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:56,720
and sharp fangs, Sarantuya hates 
strong feelings like anger and fury.  

140
00:16:58,080 --> 00:17:03,840
She is the most peaceful creature 
Timucin has ever come across.

141
00:17:04,720 --> 00:17:11,280
"You know very well what I mean," he says, 
just managing to keep control of himself.  

142
00:17:12,560 --> 00:17:22,080
"That dog! Why did you stop Chuzir killing it?" 
"Did I?" replies Sarantuya, pretending to be  

143
00:17:22,080 --> 00:17:32,880
surprised. Then she laughs quietly. It sounds like 
thunder rolling in the mountains on the horizon.

144
00:17:34,080 --> 00:17:37,760
"What if your friend Chuzir just missed?"

145
00:17:39,200 --> 00:17:45,840
"Nonsense!" replies Timucin. "Chuzir is the 
best shot I know. He never misses his target!"

146
00:17:47,120 --> 00:17:52,800
"Not even with a bent arrow?" 
says Sarantuya mockingly.

147
00:17:53,760 --> 00:17:56,160
Timucin ignores this comment.

148
00:17:57,200 --> 00:18:00,240
"He never misses his target," he insists.

149
00:18:01,040 --> 00:18:08,960
"Well then, it must be that somebody wanted 
him to miss," says Sarantuya, smirking.

150
00:18:10,480 --> 00:18:10,720
"You."

151
00:18:12,160 --> 00:18:18,880
"No," says the dragon, suddenly in a very 
serious tone of voice. "I would never do  

152
00:18:18,880 --> 00:18:22,080
anything you do not want, and you know it."

153
00:18:23,440 --> 00:18:30,160
Timucin says nothing more. Chuzir 
said nothing after missing. He simply  

154
00:18:30,160 --> 00:18:37,520
walked on for a few moments, offended. The way 
he looked at Timucin showed that he knew exactly  

155
00:18:37,520 --> 00:18:46,320
who he blamed for his unusual failure. Perhaps 
Chuzir actually knows that it is Timucin's fault.  

156
00:18:47,120 --> 00:18:51,680
Timucin has already told him 
once about his dream dragon,  

157
00:18:51,680 --> 00:18:58,320
but Chuzir's reaction was such that Timucin 
has never mentioned it again. It was years  

158
00:18:58,320 --> 00:19:04,720
ago now, and Timucin does not know if Chuzir 
remembers it at all, but you just never know.

159
00:19:06,240 --> 00:19:12,480
"You didn't really want to kill the 
dog," continues Sarantuya after a while.

160
00:19:13,440 --> 00:19:16,640
"But I was afraid of him", answers Timucin.

161
00:19:17,360 --> 00:19:25,680
"I know," says Sarantuya with a sigh, "but you 
don't need to kill every-thing you are afraid of.  

162
00:19:26,320 --> 00:19:28,960
Do you remember the first time you saw me?"

163
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:30,880
"Of course I do!"

164
00:19:31,680 --> 00:19:33,680
"You were afraid of me, too."

165
00:19:34,800 --> 00:19:40,720
"No, I wasn't," claims Timucin, 
although this is a downright lie.  

166
00:19:41,680 --> 00:19:46,960
He almost died of fright the first time 
the dragon appeared to him in a dream.

167
00:19:47,840 --> 00:19:54,080
"So," continues Sarantuya, "did you 
want to kill me because of that?"

168
00:19:55,840 --> 00:20:01,760
"Of course not!" answers Timucin, 
outraged. "I would never..."

169
00:20:01,760 --> 00:20:09,600
"... kill anything that hasn't done you any harm," 
says Sarantuya, finishing his sentence for him.  

170
00:20:10,560 --> 00:20:16,640
"I know. If it were any different, 
I would never have come to you."

171
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:22,480
Timucin does not really 
understand what she is saying, but  

172
00:20:22,480 --> 00:20:29,840
he isn't in the mood to ask questions. Sarantuya 
says many odd things that he does not understand.

173
00:20:31,040 --> 00:20:34,960
"What do you want?" he asks reluctantly.

174
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:43,840
For once, Timucin's anger seems to 
amuse Sarantuya, perhaps because  

175
00:20:43,840 --> 00:20:49,360
she too feels that, in reality, it 
is only directed against himself.

176
00:20:50,640 --> 00:20:56,320
"Really, it should be me asking 
you these questions," she answers.  

177
00:20:57,440 --> 00:21:05,680
"If I remember correctly, you were the one 
who called me, and not the other way round.  

178
00:21:08,160 --> 00:21:16,880
Since I'm here anyway... Tomorrow is a 
big day for you. A very important day."

179
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:25,440
Timucin thinks as hard as 
he can. Tomorrow? Tomorrow?

180
00:21:27,040 --> 00:21:30,480
"How so?" he asks, skeptically.

181
00:21:31,920 --> 00:21:38,800
"It's a surprise!" says Sarantuya, 
teasing him. "You will meet someone.  

182
00:21:39,520 --> 00:21:43,840
Someone who will become very important to you."

183
00:21:45,120 --> 00:21:47,200
"Who?" asks Timucin.

184
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:57,840
Yet Sarantuya does not even answer. She 
disappears with a silvery, bright laugh.
 
 
 

185
00:21:57,840 --> 00:22:02,160
CHAPTER THREE

186
00:22:02,160 --> 00:22:02,880
The Warrior

187
00:22:04,960 --> 00:22:10,720
His father Tamer wakes him the following 
morning before the sun has come up.  

188
00:22:11,680 --> 00:22:19,200
This is nothing unusual: most people in the 
village get up before dawn, and only very rarely  

189
00:22:19,200 --> 00:22:27,280
does Timucin sleep past sunrise. If he does, 
it is mostly when his father has been up too  

190
00:22:27,280 --> 00:22:33,760
long drinking or discussing matters with the 
other men - both of which have the same result.  

191
00:22:34,720 --> 00:22:42,080
What is unusual, however, is his father's 
grumpy mood and his even grumpier face.  

192
00:22:43,120 --> 00:22:53,200
This is the first thing Timucin sees as he opens 
his eyes. Tamer is a great warrior, no doubt,  

193
00:22:53,200 --> 00:23:00,240
who has killed many enemies and brought the 
tribe to respect and riches. But at the bottom  

194
00:23:00,240 --> 00:23:07,840
of his heart, he is a friendly man, a gentle 
one, especially where his son is concerned.

195
00:23:09,680 --> 00:23:16,640
This morning, however, he is not 
at all gentle. In fact, he seems  

196
00:23:16,640 --> 00:23:22,720
furious as he grasps his son's shoulder 
and shakes him roughly to wake him.  

197
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:31,520
If Timucin were not as sleepy, he would 
understand that his father really is furious.

198
00:23:32,480 --> 00:23:35,840
He rubs his eyes and looks astonished  

199
00:23:36,480 --> 00:23:42,080
as his father goes back to the small entrance 
to the tent and motions him to follow.

200
00:23:42,960 --> 00:23:48,640
Just like every morning, they look after 
the horses and drive the sheep onto the  

201
00:23:48,640 --> 00:23:56,240
pasture without saying a single word to one 
another. Then they go down to the river to  

202
00:23:56,240 --> 00:24:04,960
wash themselves in the icy waters of the Omon. 
Then his father breaks the uncomfortable silence.

203
00:24:06,160 --> 00:24:13,440
"Chuzir told me about the dog," he 
says, his voice full of reproach.  

204
00:24:15,120 --> 00:24:22,720
Timucin looks at him. He is not quite 
sure what Chuzir has told his father,  

205
00:24:22,720 --> 00:24:31,840
and so saying nothing is probably the 
cleverest thing to do. His father sighs deeply.

206
00:24:33,840 --> 00:24:44,080
"When are you going to finally become a man, my 
son?" he asks. "You are my only son, Timucin,  

207
00:24:44,080 --> 00:24:51,360
and one day you will take my place and become 
khan. But how will you be able to do that if  

208
00:24:51,360 --> 00:25:00,880
you are still a mere boy?" Timucin does not 
answer. His father does not want an answer,  

209
00:25:00,880 --> 00:25:08,880
he can feel this, and this is not the first time 
they have had this talk. Tamer may not yet have  

210
00:25:08,880 --> 00:25:17,680
said it as directly as he has now, but Timucin 
knows very well that it is a great source of pain  

211
00:25:17,680 --> 00:25:24,640
to him that his only son will not grow 
into the great warrior he wants him to be.  

212
00:25:26,320 --> 00:25:35,920
Timucin may be a passable bowman, may be good 
rider, and may just about know how to handle  

213
00:25:35,920 --> 00:25:44,400
a sword and shield, but that is not enough. 
The other boys are better than he is, even  

214
00:25:44,400 --> 00:25:52,320
the younger ones. It is not so much a question 
of his ability, his skill or even his courage.  

215
00:25:52,960 --> 00:26:00,480
It is just that he doesn't like weapons. 
He has never really understood where the  

216
00:26:00,480 --> 00:26:07,200
glow in the eyes of the warriors comes from when 
they speak of all the enemies they have slain.

217
00:26:08,480 --> 00:26:16,000
"Chuzir told me," says his father, picking 
up where he left off, "that you were scared  

218
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:19,840
stiff of the dog as it stood in front of you."

219
00:26:21,040 --> 00:26:27,600
"It was a very big dog..." answers 
Timucin, "and it was very dangerous."

220
00:26:29,520 --> 00:26:36,720
This must have been the wrong answer, 
because Tamer's face becomes even darker.

221
00:26:37,520 --> 00:26:40,080
"Did it attack you?" he asks.

222
00:26:40,800 --> 00:26:48,160
Timucin keeps silent. His father 
turns suddenly and walks back  

223
00:26:48,160 --> 00:26:54,640
towards the village with such big strides 
that Timucin has to struggle not to fall back.  

224
00:26:55,920 --> 00:26:59,360
His father does not look at 
him as he starts talking again.

225
00:27:00,080 --> 00:27:08,000
"Dogs, Timucin, are, after horses, our most 
loyal friends. They help us to watch our sheep,  

226
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:12,080
to keep our food supplies free of 
rats, and they warm us in winter  

227
00:27:12,080 --> 00:27:17,200
when the fire no longer burns enough. 
There is no need to be afraid of them!"

228
00:27:17,920 --> 00:27:26,400
"But it was growling at me!" says Timucin in his 
defence. He is not sure if this was actually the  

229
00:27:26,400 --> 00:27:33,840
case, and it is clearly not the answer that 
Tamer wants, because now he is really furious.

230
00:27:35,120 --> 00:27:41,600
"But it didn't attack you, did it? And 
even if it had, you would have had to have  

231
00:27:41,600 --> 00:27:45,440
killed it like a warrior. You had 
your bow with you, didn't you?"

232
00:27:46,560 --> 00:27:52,000
"Yes," answers Timucin 
dejectedly, "I am sorry, father."

233
00:27:53,040 --> 00:27:57,920
"Be silent!" shouts Tamer. 
"You are the son of a khan!  

234
00:27:58,640 --> 00:28:05,920
You shall never say you are sorry to anyone about 
anything! Not even to me! If you make a mistake,  

235
00:28:05,920 --> 00:28:09,760
be sure not to do it again. But never apologise!"

236
00:28:10,960 --> 00:28:16,960
"Yes father," replies Timucin. 
He almost adds "I am sorry".

237
00:28:19,440 --> 00:28:22,960
They cover the rest of the way 
back to the village in silence.  

238
00:28:24,160 --> 00:28:30,480
As they reach it over the hill, the 
village is now wide-awake and busy at work.  

239
00:28:31,680 --> 00:28:41,680
They hear children shouting, an ox mooing and, in 
the distance, the thunder of horses' hooves. When  

240
00:28:41,680 --> 00:28:48,800
they get to Tamer's yurt, which, as is his right, 
is the biggest in the village, big enough to take  

241
00:28:48,800 --> 00:28:59,200
in all the men in the entire tribe, they find it 
empty. This is unusual, and Timucin wants to leave  

242
00:28:59,200 --> 00:29:07,360
the tent and go about his daily work, which he has 
now neglected too long. But Tamer calls him back  

243
00:29:07,360 --> 00:29:13,920
with a lordly movement of his hand and gestures 
to him to stand in the middle of the tent.

244
00:29:14,880 --> 00:29:24,720
Timucin is confused, but obeys his father. His 
heart is beating hard. He has been hoping that  

245
00:29:24,720 --> 00:29:32,960
this is all over, but it seems that his father 
has not finished yet. Perhaps what Tamer has just  

246
00:29:32,960 --> 00:29:39,280
said is only the beginning? His 
heart starts to beat even faster,  

247
00:29:39,280 --> 00:29:45,520
and he clenches his fists so that his father 
does not see how badly his fingers are shaking.

248
00:29:46,640 --> 00:29:54,240
Tamer is moving around behind him, and Timucin 
asks himself what he is actually doing.  

249
00:29:55,600 --> 00:30:01,040
He does not dare to turn around, but 
keeps staring at the ashes of the fire.  

250
00:30:02,240 --> 00:30:07,840
Finally, his father returns and throws 
something to the ground in front of him.  

251
00:30:08,480 --> 00:30:15,520
It takes Timucin a while to recognise it as 
the full outfit and weaponry of a warrior.  

252
00:30:17,120 --> 00:30:26,880
There is a leather tunic and belt, a fine-woven 
chainmail shirt, boots with artfully engraved  

253
00:30:26,880 --> 00:30:37,120
metal plates, a breastplate and shield, a precious 
bronze helmet and a broad, decorated weapon-belt,  

254
00:30:37,120 --> 00:30:45,680
wrapped around a beautifully forged sword. 
There is everything he needs to be a warrior.

255
00:30:47,280 --> 00:30:49,817
"Put it on!" says Tamer.

256
00:30:49,817 --> 00:30:55,120
Timucin obeys his father, but he 
is becoming more and more nervous.  

257
00:30:56,240 --> 00:31:01,440
He knows of the existence of warriors' 
clothing because Tamer has told him  

258
00:31:01,440 --> 00:31:10,960
about it. His father always stresses that it is 
reserved for very special occasions, and Timucin  

259
00:31:10,960 --> 00:31:19,120
has never seen it before. He does not dare ask 
questions but looks quizzically at his father  

260
00:31:19,120 --> 00:31:25,360
while putting on the outfit. Finally, 
Tamer breaks the silence himself.

261
00:31:26,320 --> 00:31:32,560
"Today is a special day," he 
begins and watches closely  

262
00:31:32,560 --> 00:31:39,520
every movement Timucin's nervous hands make, 
"and I want you to make a good impression.  

263
00:31:40,640 --> 00:31:50,080
Behave yourself and do not bring shame upon our 
clan or upon me, your father. And do not worry:  

264
00:31:50,080 --> 00:31:57,840
I have told our warriors to chase all the dogs 
out of the village until our visitor has left."

265
00:31:59,120 --> 00:32:05,200
Timucin feels his ears going 
red and sinks his head in shame.

266
00:32:06,400 --> 00:32:10,080
"Who is coming to visit?" he asks nonetheless.

267
00:32:11,920 --> 00:32:19,440
"My brother in oath, Belmin, the khan 
of the Voshon tribe," answers Tamer.  

268
00:32:19,440 --> 00:32:20,400
"Have you heard of them?"

269
00:32:21,440 --> 00:32:26,240
"Yes father," answers Timucin quietly. The Voshon?  

270
00:32:26,960 --> 00:32:35,200
Of course, he has heard of them, as well as of 
Belmin, their wise and mighty khan. Belmin became  

271
00:32:35,200 --> 00:32:42,392
his father's brother in oath when he and Tamer 
were the same age as Timucin and Chuzir are now.

272
00:32:42,391 --> 00:32:52,799
The Voshon tribe has far more land than Tamer's 
tribe and is much, much richer. It is told that  

273
00:32:52,800 --> 00:32:59,840
their herds are so big that, if all their horses 
were to be driven together at once, they would  

274
00:32:59,840 --> 00:33:10,000
cover the steppe from horizon to horizon. The 
khan's yurt is said to be covered in pure gold.

275
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:18,880
Despite this wealth and power, it is told that 
they are a very peaceful tribe, and many warriors  

276
00:33:18,880 --> 00:33:25,920
laugh at them - as long as Tamer is not around 
to defend the honour of his brother in oath.

277
00:33:27,120 --> 00:33:34,160
Timucin buckles his sword-belt and then reaches 
for the last item, his helmet. He thinks for a  

278
00:33:34,160 --> 00:33:42,160
moment about whether to put it on now, but then 
decides against this and puts it under his left  

279
00:33:42,160 --> 00:33:50,400
arm. His father eyes him for a moment, looks 
him up and down and then nods his approval.

280
00:33:51,200 --> 00:33:58,640
"And what is so important about this visit 
for me?" asks Timucin. "Who am I meeting?"

281
00:33:59,440 --> 00:34:07,680
Tamer looks at him surprised, and Timucin wants 
to slap himself in the face for having asked this  

282
00:34:07,680 --> 00:34:14,160
question. It is Sarantuya who has told him that 
he will meet somebody who will affect his future,  

283
00:34:14,160 --> 00:34:22,560
not his father. He has said nothing. He looks 
at Timucin for two or three heartbeats in a way  

284
00:34:22,560 --> 00:34:32,160
that makes Timucin really very uncomfortable. 
Then, however, he answers his son's question:  

285
00:34:33,120 --> 00:34:41,680
"You are old enough now, my son, and soon you 
will be a man. It is time to find you a wife."

286
00:34:43,040 --> 00:34:54,800
"A wife?" Timucin is beyond surprised. He was 
ready for anything, just not that. "But..."

287
00:34:55,680 --> 00:35:04,960
"You are old enough, my boy," interrupts Tamer, 
"at your age, I was already married. Belmin is  

288
00:35:04,960 --> 00:35:13,200
bringing his daughter, Arbesa. She is just one 
year younger than you and, so I have heard tell,  

289
00:35:14,080 --> 00:35:21,600
very beautiful. And of course a link between 
our tribes would be to everyone's advantage."

290
00:35:22,640 --> 00:35:28,240
"But I don't know this girl 
at all," protests Timucin.

291
00:35:29,440 --> 00:35:36,880
As he has expected, his father's 
face darkens. Moments later, however,  

292
00:35:36,880 --> 00:35:48,240
a sudden and unusually gentle smile spreads across 
his face. "Son, I would never force you to marry  

293
00:35:48,240 --> 00:35:55,840
anyone you do not want to, but have a look 
at her at least. I ask for no more than that,  

294
00:35:56,800 --> 00:36:04,480
and perhaps you will like her. She will 
definitely like you, I'm very sure of that."

295
00:36:05,840 --> 00:36:10,000
Timucin looks quizzically as Tamer stops talking  

296
00:36:10,640 --> 00:36:17,200
and bends down to pick up a polished silver 
plate left from the previous evening's feast.  

297
00:36:18,400 --> 00:36:25,440
There are streaks of dried sheep's milk and 
bits of food stuck to it, but Timucin can still  

298
00:36:25,440 --> 00:36:32,800
see his own reflection in the mirror and 
understands what his father means. He really does  

299
00:36:32,800 --> 00:36:40,160
look like a warrior, magnificently equipped 
and wild, with his hair braided his strong  

300
00:36:40,160 --> 00:36:48,000
features and his lively, light blue eyes. Who 
would be able to resist him looking like this?

301
00:36:49,920 --> 00:36:57,840
Timucin is about to make a jokey remark about 
this when he thinks he feels movement behind him.  

302
00:36:59,200 --> 00:37:09,040
It is a kind of golden shimmering, like 
moonlight breaking on polished scales.  

303
00:37:10,800 --> 00:37:19,280
He quickly checks behind himself, but sees 
nothing. When he looks back at the plate, however,  

304
00:37:20,240 --> 00:37:28,800
he sees Sarantuya reflected behind him, this 
time even more clearly than in his dream.  

305
00:37:30,480 --> 00:37:32,960
She looks at him and she too  

306
00:37:33,520 --> 00:37:40,240
sees the warrior, which this wonderful 
armour, sword and helmet have made him into.

307
00:37:42,240 --> 00:37:49,840
The big gold dragon looks sad.
 
 
 

308
00:37:49,840 --> 00:37:50,640
CHAPTER FOUR

309
00:37:50,640 --> 00:37:51,760
New Arrival

310
00:37:53,680 --> 00:38:02,320
Belmin does not come until the sun is well 
past its highest point. Nevertheless, as befits  

311
00:38:02,320 --> 00:38:10,240
someone of his rank, he travels with a large 
entourage. Several riders have arrived before him  

312
00:38:10,240 --> 00:38:18,640
to give advance notice of his arrival. The whole 
village gathers to welcome him fittingly. Timucin  

313
00:38:18,640 --> 00:38:25,360
of course has a place in the first row, right 
next to his father and the other warriors.

314
00:38:26,320 --> 00:38:32,160
However, Timucin does not start towards 
the group until the baggage train can be  

315
00:38:32,160 --> 00:38:38,400
seen on the hills in the West. He is 
not in much of a hurry to get there,  

316
00:38:39,120 --> 00:38:44,880
and in even less of a hurry to meet 
either his father's brother in oath,  

317
00:38:45,680 --> 00:38:53,920
or his daughter. He has got nothing against 
girls and knows as well as the next man that  

318
00:38:53,920 --> 00:39:00,160
the children of tribal chiefs get married to 
each other in order to increase their power  

319
00:39:00,160 --> 00:39:09,440
and to secure an often all too insecure peace. 
He should not be surprised that his turn has now  

320
00:39:09,440 --> 00:39:17,120
come. He has simply believed that he has a little 
more time - perhaps another summer, maybe two.

321
00:39:18,240 --> 00:39:25,440
Of course, he will not dare to defy his 
father. But he has mixed feelings about  

322
00:39:25,440 --> 00:39:30,880
this meeting with his father's brother 
in oath and, above all, the daughter.

323
00:39:32,320 --> 00:39:39,440
As befits their status, the other boys, 
including Chuzir, wait at an appropriate distance  

324
00:39:39,440 --> 00:39:48,480
behind the warriors and the elders, yet in front 
of the women still. Timucin has to walk past them  

325
00:39:48,480 --> 00:39:57,200
in order to join his father on time. He ignores 
the other boys as usual, but greets Chuzir and  

326
00:39:57,200 --> 00:40:06,880
is about to set off even faster. Yet he notices 
Chuzir's dark expression of face and turns round  

327
00:40:06,880 --> 00:40:14,960
to him, his brow furrowed quizzically. 
Chuzir avoids his gaze and turns away.

328
00:40:16,960 --> 00:40:22,560
"What is wrong?" asks Timucin 
bluntly. He is confused.

329
00:40:23,520 --> 00:40:31,840
"Nothing," replies Chuzir curtly. Timucin 
stretches his hand out so as to seize him  

330
00:40:31,840 --> 00:40:37,840
by the shoulder, but Chuzir steps back 
quickly and Timucin pulls back his arm.  

331
00:40:38,960 --> 00:40:48,400
He feels a faint but deep stabbing pain in 
his chest: Chuzir is his brother in oath!

332
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:53,520
"You must hurry, Timucin," 
says one of the other boys,  

333
00:40:53,520 --> 00:40:58,720
"otherwise you, our future Khan, will 
arrive too late to greet your bride."

334
00:40:59,680 --> 00:41:06,880
Timucin flashes his eyes at the boy, 
but does not say anything. Ilhan,  

335
00:41:06,880 --> 00:41:16,720
the boy, is two heads taller than him and doesn't 
like him. Timucin dislikes him too, and feels that  

336
00:41:16,720 --> 00:41:25,360
he will have to fight him one day. Yet he does not 
want it to be now, so he offers Ilhan nothing more  

337
00:41:25,360 --> 00:41:34,480
than a contemptuous look and makes to go on. 
Ilhan, however, continues in a mocking tone.

338
00:41:35,440 --> 00:41:38,080
"Don't you worry! We will make sure that  

339
00:41:38,080 --> 00:41:44,000
nothing else gets in the way of our 
future khan and his bride. Woof woof!"

340
00:41:45,680 --> 00:41:49,600
This comment was followed 
by laughter from all around,  

341
00:41:50,160 --> 00:41:57,760
and Timucin feels a sudden fury, so strong that 
he wants to jump at the bigger boy and pummel him.

342
00:41:58,720 --> 00:42:07,760
Yet his fury dies away as quickly as it comes, and 
gives way to something very different and much,  

343
00:42:08,320 --> 00:42:17,360
much worse. His eyes fill with burning 
tears, and he turns back to Chuzir.  

344
00:42:18,400 --> 00:42:23,440
He steps so close to him that 
no one else can hear him speak.

345
00:42:24,640 --> 00:42:31,840
"Why did you tell them about it?" 
he whispers. His voice is shaking.

346
00:42:32,840 --> 00:42:39,440
Chuzir avoids his gaze again. Timucin 
waits for him to answer the question,  

347
00:42:40,160 --> 00:42:48,560
but he says nothing, so Timucin turns away angry 
and walks away as quickly as he can without  

348
00:42:48,560 --> 00:42:57,600
running. Behind him, the boys are laughing and 
a few of them bark again. Timucin keeps his back  

349
00:42:57,600 --> 00:43:04,720
turned to them, but it costs him all the 
strength he has to hold back the tears.

350
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:12,240
His father seems very angry when he arrives 
next to him, but he does not have the time  

351
00:43:12,240 --> 00:43:17,680
to say anything to him because, in that 
moment, the baggage train is coming by.  

352
00:43:18,800 --> 00:43:25,840
Tamer simply looks at his son angrily in a 
way that seems to promise punishment later.  

353
00:43:26,480 --> 00:43:31,360
Then he straightens his shoulders 
and gets ready to greet his guests.

354
00:43:32,880 --> 00:43:42,080
Belmin is an older, white-haired man with a 
white beard that reaches his chest. He has a  

355
00:43:42,080 --> 00:43:50,640
weather-beaten face and exudes an aura of dignity 
and power that you can almost reach out and grasp.  

356
00:43:52,320 --> 00:44:00,400
Timucin has often met men who have great 
power (including his father, of course), but  

357
00:44:00,400 --> 00:44:09,280
Belmin differs from them in one important point: 
he is the first chief he has ever met who does  

358
00:44:09,280 --> 00:44:19,760
not carry a weapon. His large entourage, too, 
is mostly unarmed. Just the two knight's right  

359
00:44:19,760 --> 00:44:27,520
and left of him have spears held upright in their 
hands, and it looks to Timucin somehow as if they  

360
00:44:27,520 --> 00:44:33,840
only have them to tie their pennants to, which 
are fluttering above their heads in the wind.

361
00:44:35,200 --> 00:44:43,120
Tamer greets his noble guest effusively, using 
the complicated and wordy greetings common to his  

362
00:44:43,120 --> 00:44:51,600
people. Timucin uses this time to have a closer 
look at the many people accompanying the khan of  

363
00:44:51,600 --> 00:45:00,000
the Voshon. Of course, there is a very particular 
person he is looking for, and he finds her a  

364
00:45:00,000 --> 00:45:08,400
little behind Belmin, flanked by two knights who, 
contrary to his first impressions, are heavily  

365
00:45:08,400 --> 00:45:19,040
armed. She is slender, wrapped up in exquisite 
garments, and about a hand shorter than him.  

366
00:45:21,120 --> 00:45:32,160
She has to be Arbesa, his future wife. Her 
face is veiled, so he cannot quite recognise  

367
00:45:32,160 --> 00:45:39,040
its features, but he thinks he sees her keen 
stare through the material and quickly looks away.

368
00:45:40,240 --> 00:45:47,920
The greeting ceremony goes on for quite some time, 
but eventually it is over and Belmin makes a brief  

369
00:45:47,920 --> 00:45:57,040
gesture, allowing his entourage to sit. Milk 
as well as other, stronger drinks are offered,  

370
00:45:57,040 --> 00:46:05,200
along with a meal, and suddenly the ceremonial 
silence, previously broken only by the exchange of  

371
00:46:05,200 --> 00:46:12,160
formalities between the khans, gives way to 
general laughter and pats on the shoulder  

372
00:46:12,160 --> 00:46:17,440
as the more than thirty riders start to 
mix with the population of the village.  

373
00:46:18,720 --> 00:46:26,000
Arbesa, too, slips down from her horse 
with a smooth movement, yet Timucin  

374
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:31,120
does not find the right moment to 
approach her or even to look at her.  

375
00:46:32,560 --> 00:46:42,160
Tamer puts his hand on his shoulder and 
pushes him in between himself and Belmin.

376
00:46:42,160 --> 00:46:45,760
"This my son, Timucin," he says.

377
00:46:46,560 --> 00:46:54,560
The old khan looks at him with his strangely 
soft eyes for a few instants. Despite  

378
00:46:54,560 --> 00:47:02,400
the tangible aura of softness and goodness 
he exudes, Timucin - who is already very  

379
00:47:02,400 --> 00:47:10,640
uncomfortable - is almost afraid of 
him. Then the khan smiles suddenly.

380
00:47:12,080 --> 00:47:19,760
"So you are Timucin," he says, 
"I have heard a lot about you.  

381
00:47:20,880 --> 00:47:28,800
I am told that you are a son who is every bit 
as honorable as his father. Is this true?"

382
00:47:30,160 --> 00:47:35,440
Timucin does not know what to answer 
and simply lowers his head in shame.  

383
00:47:36,320 --> 00:47:43,440
In this situation, this is almost 
an insult. Tamer is horrified  

384
00:47:43,440 --> 00:47:52,800
and sucks in air sharply past his teeth. Belmin, 
however, just laughs, quietly and benevolently.

385
00:47:53,760 --> 00:48:03,520
"Well, I see he really is his father's son. My 
brother in oath was never one for too many words."

386
00:48:04,640 --> 00:48:13,680
Tamer laughs, but even his laugh sounds hollow, 
and he puts another hand on Timucin's shoulder.  

387
00:48:14,400 --> 00:48:21,280
It is as if he is showing Timucin 
off as his own property, and Timucin  

388
00:48:21,280 --> 00:48:29,120
finds this degrading. He does not say anything, 
however, and keeps looking for Arbesa.  

389
00:48:30,240 --> 00:48:37,040
The girl has already gone past him, without 
even looking at him, as it seems to him,  

390
00:48:37,040 --> 00:48:44,080
and is now talking with the women. The men of the 
tribe, too, have mingled with the village people,  

391
00:48:44,080 --> 00:48:51,920
and are eating, joking and drinking with them. 
The big reception has dissolved into nothing.  

392
00:48:52,960 --> 00:49:00,480
Only his father and his father's brother in oath 
are still standing, trying to look important,  

393
00:49:01,040 --> 00:49:04,160
but they are clearly not succeeding.  

394
00:49:05,200 --> 00:49:12,240
Tamer clearly finds the situation 
embarrassing; Belmin looks amused by it all.  

395
00:49:13,120 --> 00:49:19,520
Finally, he clears his throat and gestures 
towards the big yurt in the middle of the village.

396
00:49:20,320 --> 00:49:23,840
"It was a long and tiring journey, old friend,  

397
00:49:24,560 --> 00:49:31,600
and I am thirsty. We have not seen each other 
for many years and have much to talk about."

398
00:49:32,560 --> 00:49:34,720
And talk they did.
 
 
 

399
00:49:34,720 --> 00:49:39,600
CHAPTER FIVE

400
00:49:39,600 --> 00:49:40,320
Arbesa

401
00:49:42,320 --> 00:49:50,880
Having gone to bed so early the evening before, 
Timucin ends up going to bed very late tonight. A  

402
00:49:50,880 --> 00:49:58,880
huge feast is being given in honour of the guests, 
starting just before sundown and going on until  

403
00:49:58,880 --> 00:50:08,400
far past midnight. Almost all of the clansmen are 
in Tamer's tent, eating, talking and drinking.  

404
00:50:09,280 --> 00:50:17,840
The women are barely able to keep up with serving 
food and drinks. With all the delicious food,  

405
00:50:17,840 --> 00:50:25,280
and with the hours that pass, the feasting becomes 
ever more boisterous, and the men's tongues become  

406
00:50:25,280 --> 00:50:33,920
looser. The camp echoes to the sounds of laughter 
and music and the happy voices of the men as they  

407
00:50:33,920 --> 00:50:41,200
try to outdo each other with amazing stories. 
Everyone knows that only half of the stories  

408
00:50:41,200 --> 00:50:48,240
are actually true, but that does not stop them 
being listened to intently and greatly enjoyed.

409
00:50:49,600 --> 00:50:53,840
Timucin spends the feast sitting 
at his father's right-hand side,  

410
00:50:54,480 --> 00:51:00,880
listening to the stories that the clansmen are 
so happily embellishing, but he cannot fully  

411
00:51:00,880 --> 00:51:07,680
concentrate on the proceedings. His gaze 
keeps wandering over to the veiled girl  

412
00:51:07,680 --> 00:51:15,440
next to Belmin, and when he is not looking at 
her, he thinks he can feel her eyes on him.

413
00:51:17,040 --> 00:51:25,200
At the beginning, it is an unpleasant feeling. He 
does not like being stared at without being able  

414
00:51:25,200 --> 00:51:33,200
to see the face of the person staring. After 
a while, however, it just feels slightly odd.  

415
00:51:34,160 --> 00:51:40,720
He is curious to have a look behind 
the veil. But apart from the fact that  

416
00:51:40,720 --> 00:51:46,080
this is not the done thing, he doesn't 
allow himself to make such a request.

417
00:51:47,920 --> 00:51:52,000
It is long past midnight 
when, from outside the yurt,  

418
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:55,600
they hear the typical sound of swords clashing.  

419
00:51:56,640 --> 00:52:03,280
Tamer stops talking to his brother in oath without 
finishing his sentence and then jumps up and  

420
00:52:03,280 --> 00:52:09,760
hurries out of the tent. Everyone else, including 
Belmin and of course Timucin, follow suit.

421
00:52:10,720 --> 00:52:18,320
Outside the tent, a fight is going on between one 
of Arbesa's bodyguards and a man from the village;  

422
00:52:18,320 --> 00:52:27,120
at least, that is the way it seems at first. 
Swords clash and spray sparks, light breaks on  

423
00:52:27,120 --> 00:52:35,360
shimmering metal and the links in chainmail vests. 
The two men seem to be carrying out a bizarre and  

424
00:52:35,360 --> 00:52:42,080
speedy dance around each other, exercising 
themselves in sword-fighting techniques like  

425
00:52:42,080 --> 00:52:51,280
parries and feints whilst the blades smash into 
their shields. No blood has yet been spilled,  

426
00:52:51,280 --> 00:53:00,080
as Timucin quickly recognizes, and none will 
be: the two men are laughing as they fight.  

427
00:53:00,080 --> 00:53:07,200
Arbesa's bodyguard could land a hit on the leg 
of the man fighting him, but turns the blade  

428
00:53:07,200 --> 00:53:13,840
at the last moment so that it hits him 
flat. This hurts, but is not dangerous.  

429
00:53:14,960 --> 00:53:23,200
The onlookers whoop and clap whilst Ilhan's father 
- as Timucin recognizes him, uncomfortably - hops  

430
00:53:23,200 --> 00:53:29,520
around on one leg swearing, and then lunges 
at his opponent all the more bitterly.

431
00:53:30,960 --> 00:53:35,680
Timucin too suddenly hears himself 
cheering on the two fighters  

432
00:53:35,680 --> 00:53:38,480
as he hears a high-pitched voice next to him.

433
00:53:39,200 --> 00:53:43,760
"What do you men find so 
exciting about playing war?"

434
00:53:45,200 --> 00:53:48,240
"Well, because it's just..." says Timucin.  

435
00:53:49,440 --> 00:53:55,840
Then he stops himself in mid flow and 
turns round to see who has said this.

436
00:53:56,480 --> 00:54:00,880
It is Arbesa. She has removed her veil  

437
00:54:01,440 --> 00:54:06,400
and is looking down at the two fighters 
with an expression somewhere between  

438
00:54:06,400 --> 00:54:14,880
quizzical and derogatory. She has the most 
beautiful face that Timucin has ever seen.

439
00:54:15,920 --> 00:54:19,120
"Yes...?" she asks, turning round to him.  

440
00:54:20,480 --> 00:54:30,320
Timucin looks into her crys-tal-clear, almost 
uncannily light eyes. These eyes awaken something  

441
00:54:30,320 --> 00:54:39,920
in him whose existence he has not known until that 
moment. It is as if his throat has been tied up.

442
00:54:41,360 --> 00:54:45,360
"Well, because it's... er..." he stutters.

443
00:54:46,640 --> 00:54:52,560
Arbesa's eyes flash in a way that 
can only be described as scoffing.

444
00:54:53,360 --> 00:54:58,240
"I understand. 'Because men 
just do that kind of thing',  

445
00:54:58,800 --> 00:55:06,160
right?" She laughs. "We all 
know that. The question is why?"

446
00:55:06,160 --> 00:55:11,760
"In order to measure their strength and be 
ready when they come up against the enemy,"  

447
00:55:11,760 --> 00:55:20,400
answers Timucin automatically. He feels stupid, 
and Arbesa probably thinks he is stupid too,  

448
00:55:20,400 --> 00:55:23,920
because the scorn in her eyes continues to grow.

449
00:55:25,040 --> 00:55:29,280
"The enemy?" she repeats. "Which enemy?"

450
00:55:29,920 --> 00:55:33,840
Before Timucin has the chance 
to answer, she does it herself.

451
00:55:34,880 --> 00:55:42,080
"It doesn't matter much. There's always an enemy 
around, isn't there?" Her eyes look at Timucin  

452
00:55:42,080 --> 00:55:49,040
as intently as if she were looking at him for 
the very first time. Something in her gaze  

453
00:55:49,600 --> 00:55:54,000
stabs at Timucin's heart like a thin needle.

454
00:55:54,640 --> 00:56:03,200
"You too look like a real warrior, but perhaps 
a little small," she says and covers her face  

455
00:56:03,200 --> 00:56:09,920
back up with her veil, turns around abruptly 
and walks back to the yurt with quick steps.

456
00:56:11,040 --> 00:56:18,320
Timucin looks confused and hears a cheerful 
peal of laughter behind him. A hand  

457
00:56:18,880 --> 00:56:26,560
comes down on his shoulder and, as he looks up, 
he is looking directly into Belmin's bearded face.  

458
00:56:27,520 --> 00:56:31,680
The old khan smiles, almost mischievously.

459
00:56:32,720 --> 00:56:40,320
"Yes, well, you've met my daughter now, 
then," he says. "Do you still like her?"

460
00:56:42,240 --> 00:56:50,080
Timucin says nothing - what can he say? - 
and just looks up at Belmin, taken aback.  

461
00:56:51,600 --> 00:56:59,040
He takes his hand off of Timucin's shoulder and 
motions with his head for Timucin to follow him.

462
00:56:59,920 --> 00:57:02,400
"Come, let us step together."

463
00:57:03,440 --> 00:57:10,240
Timucin looks helplessly at the two fighters; they 
have not come anywhere near finishing, and yet  

464
00:57:10,240 --> 00:57:17,840
it is a question of the honour of the tribe. That 
does not seem to bother the old khan, however, who  

465
00:57:17,840 --> 00:57:26,800
walks off slowly, away from the light and shouts 
and noise of the friendly tussle. Timucin is  

466
00:57:26,800 --> 00:57:35,040
not sure how long it will stay friendly. He knows 
Ilhan's father well, and he does not like losing.

467
00:57:36,720 --> 00:57:44,320
"Please do not be upset at Arbesa," says Belmin 
once they have walked a while. "She is still  

468
00:57:44,320 --> 00:57:51,680
young and speaks freely and from the heart. She 
will soon learn to consider her words better."

469
00:57:53,360 --> 00:58:01,760
"I am not upset at her," says Timucin hurriedly, 
"she is a girl, after all." "And very pretty one,  

470
00:58:01,760 --> 00:58:11,440
eh?" adds the father. Timucin feels himself going 
red. He does not know why, but he lowers his head  

471
00:58:11,440 --> 00:58:14,240
and hopes that Belmin does not notice.

472
00:58:15,680 --> 00:58:22,080
"She is still a child," continues the 
old khan in an amused tone of voice,  

473
00:58:22,080 --> 00:58:26,800
from which Timucin understands 
that he has noticed his blush,  

474
00:58:27,840 --> 00:58:33,520
"but we can see that she will soon be a 
good-looking young woman. If she takes after  

475
00:58:33,520 --> 00:58:41,520
her mother, she will be a real beauty. By the 
same token, she will be fiercely independent."  

476
00:58:42,400 --> 00:58:52,240
He laughs. "You can think yourself lucky to get a 
woman of her calibre. If you want her." He stands  

477
00:58:52,240 --> 00:59:01,840
still and examines Timucin with a changed, but 
still not unfriendly gaze. "So, do you want her?"

478
00:59:03,360 --> 00:59:08,160
"But of course!" answers 
Timucin hastily. "My father..."

479
00:59:08,160 --> 00:59:15,120
"... has told you how important this 
alliance is for our two tribes, and how I  

480
00:59:15,120 --> 00:59:23,040
am his oldest and best friend and his brother in 
oath. The important thing, however, is what you  

481
00:59:23,600 --> 00:59:28,560
and Arbesa want. Do you want this to happen?"

482
00:59:30,000 --> 00:59:34,560
Timucin does not answer 
straight away and, when he does,  

483
00:59:35,200 --> 00:59:39,600
he answers so openly that he surprises himself.

484
00:59:40,640 --> 00:59:48,480
"I do not know, my lord. I mean, I do not 
know her yet. She is very pretty, but..."

485
00:59:49,200 --> 00:59:58,320
"I understand," sighs Belmin. He does not seem 
upset at all. In fact, he almost sounds relieved,  

486
00:59:58,880 --> 01:00:06,960
even if Timucin does not quite understand why. 
"Then again, this is the reason we are here."  

487
01:00:07,680 --> 01:00:15,760
He gestures towards the tent to which his daughter 
has walked back. "Arbesa is waiting for you in  

488
01:00:15,760 --> 01:00:25,200
your tent. Go to her and get to know her better. 
We shall stay for a few days, and if you still  

489
01:00:25,200 --> 01:00:31,840
think she is the right one for you - and she 
thinks you are the right one for her - then you  

490
01:00:31,840 --> 01:00:40,640
will return with us and spend the rest of the 
year at our village." He smiles warmly. "Now,  

491
01:00:41,360 --> 01:00:47,440
get going. If I know my daughter, she 
doesn't like being kept waiting..."
 
 
 

492
01:00:47,440 --> 01:00:51,120
CHAPTER SIX

493
01:00:51,120 --> 01:00:52,000
The Prophecy

494
01:00:54,400 --> 01:01:01,120
He does not go straight back to his tent, 
but stops by the fight to see how it ends.  

495
01:01:02,080 --> 01:01:10,320
It lasts for some time and gets ever more bitter. 
Well, at least Ilhan's father becomes more bitter.  

496
01:01:10,880 --> 01:01:17,840
There is some blood too, even though the wounds 
are only small, harmless cuts. But Timucin is  

497
01:01:17,840 --> 01:01:27,360
pleased when Tamer and Belmin step in and declare 
the fight a tie. Belmin's warrior looks happy and  

498
01:01:27,360 --> 01:01:37,200
laughs as he embraces his opponent. Ilhan's father 
is clearly unhappy, however, and Timucin sees  

499
01:01:37,200 --> 01:01:43,920
that he would quite happily take his sword and 
finish the fight if the two khans were not there.

500
01:01:45,680 --> 01:01:51,280
The first fight is followed by others 
between Belmin's men and village warriors,  

501
01:01:51,280 --> 01:01:57,200
most are just harmless tussles. The 
two khans, as well as most of the men,  

502
01:01:57,760 --> 01:02:04,560
return to the fire to continue the celebrations, 
and Timucin sits down with them without having  

503
01:02:04,560 --> 01:02:12,560
been asked. To judge by the look his father gives 
him, he does not like this, but he says nothing  

504
01:02:13,120 --> 01:02:17,120
and lets Timucin sit next to 
him for far longer than usual.  

505
01:02:18,240 --> 01:02:26,000
Not long before morning, Timucin finally 
gets up and goes to his yurt. He can almost  

506
01:02:26,000 --> 01:02:34,240
feel the strange looks Belmin gives him like 
a warm hand between his shoulder blades.

507
01:02:34,240 --> 01:02:42,000
It is dark and warm in his tent as he enters 
the tent. He has been hoping he will find  

508
01:02:42,000 --> 01:02:47,840
Arbesa asleep, and her regular, shallow 
breathing seems to confirm this hope.  

509
01:02:48,400 --> 01:02:54,560
Timucin does not make a light, and tries 
to undress without making any noise.  

510
01:02:55,520 --> 01:03:01,840
The metal on his suit of armour makes this 
impossible, however, it clinks and rattles.  

511
01:03:03,440 --> 01:03:11,120
Arbesa's breathing does not change. But 
when he slips under the warm sheepskin  

512
01:03:11,840 --> 01:03:18,560
and carefully lies down back-to-back 
with her, she raises her head and speaks.

513
01:03:20,560 --> 01:03:30,160
"So, all the fights are over and the 
great warrior returns tired from battle."  

514
01:03:30,160 --> 01:03:35,920
Her voice is quiet, derogatory 
and not at all sleepy.

515
01:03:38,160 --> 01:03:45,360
Timucin grounds his teeth in anger, not 
so much at Arbesa's words, but at himself  

516
01:03:45,360 --> 01:03:52,720
for actually believing that, he would get off 
so lightly. His reason tells him to say nothing  

517
01:03:53,280 --> 01:04:01,440
and pretend to be asleep; but this is perhaps 
the first, and definitely not the last time  

518
01:04:01,440 --> 01:04:08,560
he realizes how pointless it is to use a 
word like reason when talking to a woman.

519
01:04:10,560 --> 01:04:15,040
"It was just a bit of fun," he 
answers, without raising his head.

520
01:04:16,400 --> 01:04:23,440
"Yes, of course. I think it's great fun 
to watch two men going at each other with  

521
01:04:23,440 --> 01:04:28,480
sharp iron blades and hitting each 
other until they bleed," she replies.

522
01:04:29,760 --> 01:04:35,760
This makes Timucin very angry, but he 
does not really know with whom he is so  

523
01:04:35,760 --> 01:04:44,320
angry. He remains silent for a few moments, then 
he sits up, shoves the sheepskin to the side  

524
01:04:44,320 --> 01:04:50,480
and feels around in the dark until he 
finds a flint and the small oil lamp.  

525
01:04:51,680 --> 01:04:59,440
He is so angry that his hands are trembling and 
it takes him five or six attempts to get the wick.  

526
01:05:00,160 --> 01:05:07,040
Once he has finally succeeded, he is still clumsy 
enough to burn his fingers on the tiny flame.  

527
01:05:07,680 --> 01:05:14,960
Arbesa's eyes glint with disdain 
as he turns to her. She too  

528
01:05:14,960 --> 01:05:23,280
has sat up and pushed the cover down to her 
knees. She is wearing nothing more than a very  

529
01:05:23,280 --> 01:05:34,080
thin dress, through which Timucin can see almost 
everything. It embarrasses him. He looks down.

530
01:05:35,680 --> 01:05:41,440
"Why are you so shy, great 
warrior?" asks Arbesa tauntingly.  

531
01:05:42,720 --> 01:05:47,520
Timucin says nothing in reply, 
but feels himself going red again.

532
01:05:48,960 --> 01:05:56,720
"You are not embarrassed, are you?" continues the 
girl, pretending to blink in surprise. "I mean,  

533
01:05:57,280 --> 01:06:02,560
I don't know much about the customs of your 
people, but isn't it usual for the warrior  

534
01:06:02,560 --> 01:06:11,520
to return to his woman after a successful day's 
battling and lie with her?" He does not answer.

535
01:06:12,640 --> 01:06:14,960
After a brief pause, she adds:  

536
01:06:15,840 --> 01:06:22,640
"Well, if they've survived and have 
more to do than just bleed in silence."

537
01:06:24,160 --> 01:06:30,640
"You do not have to sleep here," says Timucin, 
annoyed. "If you do not like my company,  

538
01:06:30,640 --> 01:06:34,320
I can quite happily ask my father to 
provide you with your own quarters."

539
01:06:36,080 --> 01:06:44,560
Arbesa keeps smiling. The yellow light of 
the oil lamp makes her face appear even more  

540
01:06:44,560 --> 01:06:52,960
beautiful than before, and despite his growing 
fury, he is incapable of turning away from her.  

541
01:06:54,160 --> 01:07:01,840
Moreover, there is a brief moment in which she 
seems to realise that she may have gone too far  

542
01:07:02,800 --> 01:07:06,160
and is frightened. It was, however,  

543
01:07:06,720 --> 01:07:15,200
just a very brief moment, then her beautiful face 
becomes just as scornful as ever, if not worse.

544
01:07:16,720 --> 01:07:22,080
"Then again," she continues, 
as if he has not said anything,  

545
01:07:22,080 --> 01:07:27,440
"you look far better without those silly 
clothes. It must be awfully uncomfortable  

546
01:07:27,440 --> 01:07:31,840
to walk around with more than your 
own weight on your body in iron."

547
01:07:33,120 --> 01:07:40,240
Timucin instinctively looks down at himself, and 
Arbesa says quietly and, although he would not  

548
01:07:40,240 --> 01:07:47,840
have thought it possible, more scornfully: 
"Just don't you go getting any ideas."

549
01:07:49,840 --> 01:07:56,640
"Ideas? I don't know what to think at 
all," replies Timucin sharply. Well,  

550
01:07:57,200 --> 01:08:05,600
he means it to sound sharp, but it sounds more 
pathetic than anything, even to his own ears.  

551
01:08:05,600 --> 01:08:11,360
He is so red that he does not really 
need the lamp to light up his yurt.

552
01:08:12,640 --> 01:08:19,520
Arbesa stops talking and, although Timucin 
is not looking at her directly, he can feel  

553
01:08:19,520 --> 01:08:26,720
that her facial expression has changed. After 
what seems like an eternity, she speaks again.

554
01:08:28,560 --> 01:08:35,360
"I'm sorry. I didn't mean to 
hurt you." Timucin is surprised.

555
01:08:36,480 --> 01:08:41,840
"You didn't hurt me," says Timucin, 
lying without much conviction.  

556
01:08:43,040 --> 01:08:46,400
"And you need not apologise to anyone", he adds.

557
01:08:47,280 --> 01:08:50,160
"Why?" says Arbesa with a furrowed brow.

558
01:08:50,960 --> 01:08:55,280
"Because you might be the wife of 
a khan one of these days," he says,  

559
01:08:56,160 --> 01:09:01,680
"and the wife of a khan never 
apologizes to anyone for anything."

560
01:09:03,280 --> 01:09:07,760
The girl looks at him 
thoughtfully for a long moment.

561
01:09:09,760 --> 01:09:16,480
"And who taught you such rubbish?" she 
asks in a soft but confused tone of voice.

562
01:09:17,520 --> 01:09:24,080
"My father!" answers Timucin loudly. 
"And it is not rubbish! It is the truth!"

563
01:09:25,200 --> 01:09:29,600
"Because your father is the 
khan, and because the khan  

564
01:09:29,600 --> 01:09:37,280
always speaks the truth, even if what he 
says is not true, you mean?" asks Arbesa.

565
01:09:38,320 --> 01:09:46,640
In that instant, her words make Timucin so angry 
that he would like to grab her and shake her  

566
01:09:46,640 --> 01:09:53,920
until she takes them back and says she is sorry. 
Then he realizes what he has just been thinking  

567
01:09:54,720 --> 01:09:57,600
and laughs at himself against his own will.

568
01:10:00,400 --> 01:10:02,800
"You're probably right," he says.

569
01:10:04,160 --> 01:10:06,640
Arbesa is quiet again for a while.  

570
01:10:07,840 --> 01:10:14,640
She sits up again, pulls her knees to her body 
and wraps her arms around them, and Timucin  

571
01:10:14,640 --> 01:10:23,440
finds it more and more difficult not to blatantly 
stare at her. He manages it somehow, but he is  

572
01:10:23,440 --> 01:10:31,440
relatively sure that the girl knows what is going 
on inside him. Not that he understands it himself.

573
01:10:33,440 --> 01:10:37,120
"I didn't want to offend 
you," says Arbesa finally.

574
01:10:38,560 --> 01:10:45,200
"You haven't offended me," replies Timucin 
and realizes only as he speaks these words  

575
01:10:45,840 --> 01:10:50,000
that they are the truth. She has not offended him.

576
01:10:51,120 --> 01:10:54,640
"But tell me, why are you so hostile?"

577
01:10:56,800 --> 01:11:06,880
"Am I so hostile?" asks Arbesa. She leans her 
chin on her knees and looks up at him, amused.  

578
01:11:08,160 --> 01:11:15,600
Then she shrugs her shoulders. There is 
something about the mischievous glint in her eyes  

579
01:11:16,240 --> 01:11:24,960
that makes Timucin remember something vaguely, but 
he does not know what. Whatever it is, however,  

580
01:11:25,680 --> 01:11:34,800
it is familiar and fills him with a feeling of 
sudden warmth. The feeling is so strong that  

581
01:11:34,800 --> 01:11:41,920
he has to stop himself from just hugging her. 
"I'm just not used to all of this, you know."

582
01:11:43,280 --> 01:11:45,680
"All of what?" asks Timucin.

583
01:11:47,360 --> 01:11:52,400
"All these warriors and weapons 
and fun you have fighting."

584
01:11:53,680 --> 01:12:00,000
"I understand," says Timucin, 
"I've heard tell that your tribe is  

585
01:12:00,000 --> 01:12:04,320
very peaceful." He does not think 
that he has said anything wrong,  

586
01:12:04,320 --> 01:12:11,360
but suddenly Arbesa raises her head and an 
angry crease appears between her thin eyebrows.

587
01:12:12,800 --> 01:12:16,960
"That's right, just go ahead and 
say what you think!" she snaps.  

588
01:12:17,600 --> 01:12:21,840
"You think we are tribe of cowards, 
don't you? That we don't like fighting."  

589
01:12:23,120 --> 01:12:30,480
Timucin is about to contradict this, and will 
probably end up apologizing to her again, but the  

590
01:12:30,480 --> 01:12:37,280
girl does not let him speak a word. She continues 
speaking, louder than before and more angrily.

591
01:12:38,000 --> 01:12:41,280
"You needn't have any qualms 
about speaking freely.  

592
01:12:41,280 --> 01:12:46,320
I may still be a child, but I know very well 
what other tribes think and say about us."

593
01:12:48,400 --> 01:12:54,080
"I did not say that I thought your people 
were cowards," says Timucin in his defence,  

594
01:12:54,080 --> 01:12:57,280
"but what kind of khan has 
a tribe without warriors?"

595
01:12:58,400 --> 01:13:09,040
"A very wise khan, perhaps?" asks Arbesa. Her fury 
disappears as quickly as it came. Yet something  

596
01:13:09,040 --> 01:13:17,840
has changed. The tender bond between them that 
appeared a few moments back has been torn.

597
01:13:18,560 --> 01:13:22,320
"But how do you expect to defend 
your land and your property  

598
01:13:22,320 --> 01:13:27,440
against enemies who may want to rob you 
of it?" asks Timucin half-heartedly.

599
01:13:28,720 --> 01:13:33,520
"No one has tried as yet," answers Arbesa softly.

600
01:13:34,240 --> 01:13:39,360
"Yes, perhaps because there is no honour 
in winning against an enemy that cannot  

601
01:13:39,360 --> 01:13:46,080
defend itself," replies Timucin. 
He regrets having said these words  

602
01:13:46,080 --> 01:13:51,040
as soon as he has said them. 
Arbesa is not offended though;  

603
01:13:51,040 --> 01:13:56,800
she simply shrugs her shoulders and nods in 
the direction of the entrance to the tent.

604
01:13:58,000 --> 01:14:05,040
"How odd. I thought I just watched my 
bodyguard win against your man. Simply  

605
01:14:05,040 --> 01:14:13,920
because my people do not enjoy fighting, we are 
not defenseless. You should try to listen to her."

606
01:14:13,920 --> 01:14:22,880
"To her?" asks Timucin, not understanding what 
Arbesa means. She does not answer, however,  

607
01:14:22,880 --> 01:14:28,640
and lies down, pulls up the cover to 
her shoulders and turns herself in it  

608
01:14:28,640 --> 01:14:33,760
so that there is nothing left for Timucin to 
protect himself from the cold of the night.

609
01:14:34,640 --> 01:14:42,080
He sits silently for some time looking at the 
girl as she pretends to sleep before he puts  

610
01:14:42,080 --> 01:14:51,600
out the light. He lies straight and waits for 
either sleep or the cold, whichever comes first.

611
01:14:55,680 --> 01:15:02,960
The cold is the first of the two, and it 
stops him sleeping. After a while, however,  

612
01:15:02,960 --> 01:15:09,840
Timucin finds himself once again in the 
silvery moonlight of his dream world.  

613
01:15:10,800 --> 01:15:21,440
Usually (not always, but almost always), he has 
difficulty making out exact forms in his dreams,  

614
01:15:22,160 --> 01:15:32,000
but tonight he can see more than just vague 
ghosts under a starry sky. It is still a dark,  

615
01:15:32,000 --> 01:15:42,560
nighttime world, but not quite as impenetrable 
as usual. Behind Sarantuya, he can see hills on  

616
01:15:42,560 --> 01:15:52,800
a distant horizon covered by woods, and a silver, 
winding river. No steppe, and no traces of people.  

617
01:15:53,920 --> 01:16:03,040
Timucin can feel that this is a world untouched 
by the hand of man. He has an almost physical  

618
01:16:03,040 --> 01:16:12,720
sense of great age and of indescribable power, 
and this comes not only from the huge dragon,  

619
01:16:12,720 --> 01:16:20,720
but from the fabric of this world itself, a 
world which Sarantuya does not often let him see.

620
01:16:22,160 --> 01:16:32,640
"Now, did I promise too much?" asks Sarantuya. 
She is in a cheerful mood - well, as cheerful  

621
01:16:32,640 --> 01:16:42,080
as a dragon the size of ten oxen can appear, at 
least. There is a glint of mischief in her eyes,  

622
01:16:42,080 --> 01:16:49,280
and her long, scaly tail seems to thump on 
the floor to the rhythm of some silent music.

623
01:16:51,120 --> 01:16:56,400
"Wasn't that an exciting day? Well? Wasn't it?"

624
01:16:58,160 --> 01:17:07,520
"Yes," admits Timucin. Then he pulls a face. 
"Well, at least it was for some of us here."

625
01:17:08,960 --> 01:17:14,960
"Oh, don't be like that about it!" 
answers the dragon in a jovial tone,  

626
01:17:14,960 --> 01:17:18,240
which Timucin just does not understand.

627
01:17:19,920 --> 01:17:23,440
"Come on! Every man in the village would give his  

628
01:17:23,440 --> 01:17:28,400
eye teeth to share his yurt with the 
daughter of such of a mighty khan!"

629
01:17:29,680 --> 01:17:34,080
"Yes, but she is a pain in 
the neck!" says Timucin.

630
01:17:35,440 --> 01:17:40,480
"Pain in the neck? We have 
heard those words spoken before  

631
01:17:40,480 --> 01:17:48,400
about the son of certain khan in your 
village..." The dragon lays her head sideways.

632
01:17:49,440 --> 01:17:54,800
"So why is she such a pain? 
Because she says the truth?"

633
01:17:56,160 --> 01:18:04,080
Timucin is offended, but does not say anything; 
he knows there is no use. When Sarantuya  

634
01:18:04,080 --> 01:18:10,000
has decided to talk about a certain topic, 
then she talks about it - and that is that.

635
01:18:11,200 --> 01:18:18,080
"Yes, but she laughed at me," he says 
after some time, "and insulted my father."

636
01:18:20,000 --> 01:18:25,840
"No, she didn't," says Sarantuya, shaking 
her head so that he does not start to  

637
01:18:25,840 --> 01:18:32,880
contradict her. Her smile disappears 
and her face looks worried, quizzical.

638
01:18:34,400 --> 01:18:41,440
"Nevertheless, I feel resentment in 
you, my young friend. What went wrong?"

639
01:18:43,440 --> 01:18:50,960
At first, Timucin wants to deny everything, 
but that would be pointless. Even if Timucin  

640
01:18:50,960 --> 01:18:56,240
tries to hide things, Sarantuya can 
read his thoughts and he knows it.  

641
01:18:57,040 --> 01:19:02,000
Nevertheless, she always insists 
on him saying them out loud.

642
01:19:03,200 --> 01:19:05,200
"Chuzir," he admits.

643
01:19:06,320 --> 01:19:11,680
"Your friend or, I beg your 
pardon, your brother in oath now.  

644
01:19:12,800 --> 01:19:16,240
That makes him more than 
just a friend, doesn't it?"

645
01:19:17,520 --> 01:19:22,400
"Some brother in oath!" says 
Timucin. "He told everyone about it!"

646
01:19:24,240 --> 01:19:29,360
"About what?" asks the dragon, 
pretending not to know.

647
01:19:30,480 --> 01:19:35,360
"About the thing with the dog," he 
answers angrily. "Now everyone in the  

648
01:19:35,360 --> 01:19:40,000
village knows that I am afraid of dogs. 
Not just my father, but all of them."

649
01:19:42,000 --> 01:19:49,840
"And what is so bad about that? I know that you 
know this already, but I shall say it again:  

650
01:19:50,480 --> 01:19:56,080
even the heart of the bravest 
warrior is not free of fear.  

651
01:19:57,280 --> 01:20:06,480
Only the most stupid people have no fear of 
anything, and these people do not live very long.  

652
01:20:07,680 --> 01:20:13,120
But that is beside the point. 
Even we dragons know fear."

653
01:20:14,640 --> 01:20:15,600
"Fear of what?"

654
01:20:17,360 --> 01:20:25,920
"You would not understand it," answers Sarantuya 
mysteriously. "And this is not what we are talking  

655
01:20:25,920 --> 01:20:34,800
about. Now, tell me, what is so bad about 
everyone knowing you are afraid of something?"

656
01:20:36,400 --> 01:20:44,560
"Not just something," answers Timucin, 
"but dogs! Mangy little mutts!  

657
01:20:44,560 --> 01:20:50,800
Everyone will laugh at me." Well, to be 
precise, they are already laughing, he thinks.

658
01:20:52,960 --> 01:21:01,120
"No one will laugh at you when you are khan," 
says Sarantuya. "And what takes more courage?  

659
01:21:02,000 --> 01:21:09,680
To face the scorn of your tribesmen because of 
who you are, or to fight with - what did you call  

660
01:21:09,680 --> 01:21:18,640
it - a mangy little mutt? You could have beaten 
it to death if you had wanted. You are strong."  

661
01:21:20,640 --> 01:21:25,760
"No, I am a coward," says Timucin bitterly.

662
01:21:27,120 --> 01:21:34,880
"No, you are not!" says Sarantuya, almost 
angrily. "You were afraid of this dog,  

663
01:21:34,880 --> 01:21:40,240
but you were even more afraid of people 
finding this out and laughing at you.  

664
01:21:41,200 --> 01:21:49,040
A real coward kills what he fears, so 
that no one finds out about his fear."

665
01:21:50,560 --> 01:21:59,360
Timucin thinks about the mighty teeth and the 
wild look in the dog's eyes. He doubts whether  

666
01:21:59,360 --> 01:22:04,960
the animal really was all that harmless, 
but does not say anything for the moment.

667
01:22:06,640 --> 01:22:10,000
"I still don't understand why he did it, though!"  

668
01:22:10,000 --> 01:22:17,280
he continues. "He is supposed to be my 
best friend, and he betrayed me! Why?"

669
01:22:18,800 --> 01:22:21,040
"Because, unlike you,  

670
01:22:21,920 --> 01:22:33,840
in the depths of his heart he really is a coward!" 
answers Sarantuya quietly. "And he is furious."

671
01:22:35,600 --> 01:22:42,640
"Furious? At me? But why me? I 
have never done anything to him!"  

672
01:22:43,920 --> 01:22:50,560
"He missed the dog. For the first 
time ever he missed a target,  

673
01:22:51,280 --> 01:22:58,800
and he blames you. And he is not entirely 
wrong, if you think about it a moment."

674
01:23:00,560 --> 01:23:06,080
"Why? Because my arrow was bent?" says Timucin.

675
01:23:06,080 --> 01:23:13,600
"Well, that is certainly what he thinks," 
says Sarantuya, winking conspiratorially,  

676
01:23:14,320 --> 01:23:20,240
"but you and I both know why he really missed."

677
01:23:20,240 --> 01:23:28,640
Timucin keeps quiet. What Sarantuya says 
does not make anything better. In any case,  

678
01:23:28,640 --> 01:23:33,840
it is unimportant why he is 
to blame for Chuzir's failure.

679
01:23:34,720 --> 01:23:39,760
"He is already regretting having 
told everyone," says Sarantuya,  

680
01:23:40,640 --> 01:23:47,840
"so don't be angry with him. You 
are friends after all, right?"

681
01:23:48,400 --> 01:23:54,320
"Well, that's what I thought until 
now, yes," says Timucin, upset.

682
01:23:55,840 --> 01:24:05,440
"Friendship also means forgiving," says Sarantuya. 
"In fact, that is what it means above all."

683
01:24:07,120 --> 01:24:14,880
Timucin is about to make a nasty comment when 
he notices movement in the corner of his eye  

684
01:24:14,880 --> 01:24:21,840
and turns round, frightened. 
Something rushes away. It is big,  

685
01:24:21,840 --> 01:24:30,880
scaly and snake-like, and disappears so quickly 
that he cannot make it out. Was it perhaps a...?

686
01:24:31,760 --> 01:24:38,480
Surprised, he turns back to Sarantuya, who 
answers his question before he has asked it.

687
01:24:39,360 --> 01:24:41,600
"Don't ask, my little friend.  

688
01:24:42,720 --> 01:24:50,480
I can't answer, and he won't talk to you either. 
We only talk to the people we belong to."

689
01:24:52,000 --> 01:24:56,080
It takes a moment for Timucin 
to understand what she means.

690
01:24:57,280 --> 01:25:04,480
"So... you mean that somebody else here 
is speaking to a dragon right now?"  

691
01:25:05,600 --> 01:25:11,600
he murmurs. A moment ago, he would 
never have believed that dragons  

692
01:25:11,600 --> 01:25:18,720
could grin. But Sarantuya can, 
and she grins almost shamelessly.

693
01:25:19,920 --> 01:25:23,200
"Yes. For some time, too!"

694
01:25:25,440 --> 01:25:33,200
It takes Timucin even longer to understand, 
then he turns around half-terrified to Arbesa.  

695
01:25:34,720 --> 01:25:43,040
She is not there, of course, because 
this is just a dream. Sarantuya giggles.

696
01:25:45,360 --> 01:25:53,840
"Arbesa?" he murmurs skeptically. 
"You mean... she too has a dragon?"

697
01:25:55,920 --> 01:25:59,680
"Well, actually it's us dragons who have you  

698
01:26:00,480 --> 01:26:07,840
and not you us," says Sarantuya, a 
little offended, "but yes, she does."

699
01:26:09,120 --> 01:26:11,440
"Oh," says Timucin.

700
01:26:12,800 --> 01:26:20,400
"Oh. Yes 'oh' indeed" says Sarantuya, 
making fun of his tone of voice.

701
01:26:21,440 --> 01:26:24,240
"So you thought you were the only one?"

702
01:26:26,160 --> 01:26:33,520
"If I'm honest, yes I did." In 
fact, if he is completely honest,  

703
01:26:34,320 --> 01:26:40,000
he is not even sure whether 
Sarantuya actually exists at all.

704
01:26:41,760 --> 01:26:46,400
"Well, in that case, I'm going 
to have to disappoint you,"  

705
01:26:46,400 --> 01:26:52,320
says Sarantuya, teasing him, "you're not 
as special as all that, my little Khan!"

706
01:26:54,400 --> 01:26:59,440
"But why did Arbesa not say 
anything about it?" mumbles Timucin.

707
01:27:01,200 --> 01:27:05,040
"Why should she? She doesn't know you at all."  

708
01:27:06,320 --> 01:27:13,440
Timucin thinks back: in fact, 
she did say something about it.

709
01:27:14,720 --> 01:27:22,320
"Anyway, it's nothing special to her. Almost 
everyone in her tribe has a dragon-friend."

710
01:27:24,240 --> 01:27:28,960
"The whole tribe?" says Timucin, astonished.

711
01:27:29,920 --> 01:27:34,000
"Well, almost all of them," answers Sarantuya,  

712
01:27:34,640 --> 01:27:41,840
"because they are a very peaceful people, 
and dragons love peaceful people."

713
01:27:43,280 --> 01:27:53,120
"What? Dragons, of all creatures!" he says. 
He regrets this immediately, but of course,  

714
01:27:53,120 --> 01:27:59,840
Sarantuya would have heard these words even if 
he had just thought them. She looks offended,  

715
01:28:00,880 --> 01:28:04,960
upset and ever so slightly angry.

716
01:28:06,720 --> 01:28:14,880
"You think that, just because we are big 
and strong, we are dangerous?" she asks.  

717
01:28:16,160 --> 01:28:23,360
Timucin discovers that it is possible to 
blush in a dream too. He keeps silent.

718
01:28:23,360 --> 01:28:30,800
"We are big and very strong," continues 
Sarantuya, sounding suddenly very serious  

719
01:28:30,800 --> 01:28:36,320
and still slightly angry, "so no 
one can be of any danger to us,  

720
01:28:37,360 --> 01:28:43,600
but why should this make us into 
beasts? We are not like you people!"

721
01:28:45,520 --> 01:28:50,880
Timucin wants to say something, but 
Sarantuya motions him to keep quiet with an  

722
01:28:50,880 --> 01:28:54,400
astonishingly human movement of her right paw.

723
01:28:55,440 --> 01:29:03,360
"I know what people say about us. You all 
think we are monsters, horrible monsters who  

724
01:29:03,360 --> 01:29:09,840
eat people and animals and burn 
land with our breath of fire."  

725
01:29:10,960 --> 01:29:16,880
She winks at him before continuing. 
"That's about the size of it, right?"

726
01:29:18,160 --> 01:29:20,080
"Hm," says Timucin.

727
01:29:21,280 --> 01:29:28,320
"But that is not the way it is. We are 
just as big and strong as you think,  

728
01:29:28,320 --> 01:29:38,240
even stronger - just one of us could wipe your 
tribe off the face of the earth. But why would we  

729
01:29:38,240 --> 01:29:48,000
do that? No dragon has ever killed a person, and 
we never shall, as long as you are in existence."

730
01:29:49,920 --> 01:29:55,280
"I'm sorry," murmurs Timucin, 
"I didn't mean to hurt you."

731
01:29:56,640 --> 01:30:05,840
"I know," says Sarantuya in her usual, 
softer tones. Suddenly, she starts giggling.

732
01:30:06,560 --> 01:30:14,480
"Did I just mishear something, or did you 
just say sorry to me, son of the khan?"

733
01:30:15,600 --> 01:30:20,640
Timucin is silent and Sarantuya is serious again.

734
01:30:21,520 --> 01:30:25,200
"Well, you would have asked 
that question at some point,  

735
01:30:25,840 --> 01:30:33,840
and I've just answered it. Perhaps this was the 
right moment, now that you have met your wife."

736
01:30:34,720 --> 01:30:38,320
"We are not married yet!" objects Timucin,  

737
01:30:39,040 --> 01:30:45,440
but Sarantuya shakes her head, her 
scales jingling lightly as she does.

738
01:30:46,960 --> 01:30:53,680
"She will be your wife, young Khan. You 
will live a long and happy life together,  

739
01:30:54,400 --> 01:30:57,840
even though you will betray her one day."

740
01:30:59,280 --> 01:31:03,920
"Me? Never!" says Timucin, outraged.

741
01:31:04,480 --> 01:31:13,280
"Yes, yes, you will," says Sarantuya softly, 
"but don't worry - she will forgive you."

742
01:31:14,720 --> 01:31:20,960
"You can see into the future?" 
says Timucin, eyes wide open.

743
01:31:22,400 --> 01:31:24,960
"Not everything," says Sarantuya,  

744
01:31:26,000 --> 01:31:30,800
"We dragons do not see into the 
future, not in the way you think."

745
01:31:32,560 --> 01:31:38,160
"Well, you did predict that I was going to meet 
somebody who would be of great importance to me."

746
01:31:39,120 --> 01:31:47,680
"That wasn't the future, my little friend that was 
just one day. But we do see a lot, that is true.  

747
01:31:49,040 --> 01:31:57,840
Some of the paths into the future are clear and 
wide, some thin and blurred, or even forked.  

748
01:31:58,720 --> 01:32:06,480
I can tell you that Arbesa will become your wife 
and that you will live long and happily together.  

749
01:32:07,680 --> 01:32:13,040
What you do in that time is 
up to you. I can't see that."

750
01:32:14,160 --> 01:32:19,280
"And even if you could see it, you 
wouldn't tell me," says Timucin.

751
01:32:21,040 --> 01:32:24,160
"That's true," answers Sarantuya cheerfully,  

752
01:32:25,040 --> 01:32:29,840
"but you will find the right way 
in any case. I'm almost sure!"

753
01:32:31,760 --> 01:32:32,400
"Almost?"

754
01:32:34,000 --> 01:32:40,400
"Almost," insists Sarantuya, 
"because even we dragons don't know  

755
01:32:40,400 --> 01:32:47,360
everything. We have neither the right nor 
the power to get involved in your lives.  

756
01:32:48,400 --> 01:32:56,720
But you have a good heart and I believe in 
you. Otherwise I wouldn't have chosen you1."

757
01:32:58,320 --> 01:33:00,080
"Chosen?" repeats Timucin.

